people will view LLMs the same way we view IDEs now. the vim elitists who programmed on a PDP-11 (though I guess it'd be ed, not vim or vi) likely view IDEs the way we view ChatGPT, or how assembly developers view the compiler, or who modern artists view photoshop/krita, or animation tweens. anything that appears after the era you grew up in will be seen as radical, sometimes for the worst, sometimes for the better, and there is no individual fixed point. some of the professors who taught me a few years ago now include chatgpt in their assignments in the same vein developers today collaborate, use IDE tools like live templates, autocomplete, autorefactor, tools that boomers might say "should be learned manually to get the ropes". do i discourage chatgpt on aoc because i'm against ai? no, i'm against an unfair, inconsistent battlefield. if everyone used ai/were aware of it, then sure, make an ai aoc leaderboard. but there are still people who get by without it who dont want to be compared to those who do. but where's the line? i sometimes go on wikipedia to relearn floyd-warshall during aoc. is that cheating? what is cheating? is it really that deep? some people do aoc at snails pace because they want to learn fkn haskell. aoc's questions have a good balance of fluff and requirements parsing that if i wasn't competing with my friends, i'd probably be using chatgpt to grok and practice prompt engineering because Eric does a really good job of obscuring requirements to get you to really dig deep into the test data and ask questions. and in that case chatgpt becomes a useful tool. as long as you are not doing it just to spite the people on the leaderboard i guess.
